Core math pattern

A sheet is a 2D domain:

S \subset \mathbb{R}^2

A finished origami object is a 3D embedded structure:

F(S) \subset \mathbb{R}^3

The crease pattern is not the object. It is the operator graph that transforms the sheet into the object.

C = \{c_i, \theta_i, t_i\}

Where:

* c_i = crease line / fold boundary
* \theta_i = fold angle
* t_i = order / dependency timing

So the true hidden thing is:

\[
S \xrightarrow{C} O
\]

Flat sheet → crease operator graph → object.

Reverse engineering is:

O \rightarrow \hat{C}

Final artifact → best-estimate hidden generative pattern.

That is the math of reconstructing invisible cause from visible form.

